<h1>How to Stack 5 Income Streams Without Burnout</h1>
<p class="lead">Stop chasing one big break. Build small, repeatable income layers instead. This guide shows you the exact order to add them so you stay sane.</p>

<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1460925895917-afdab827c52f?w=1200&h=630&fit=crop" alt="Income streams dashboard" class="hero">

<h2>Layer 1: Affiliate income — weeks 1-4</h2>
<p>Write 3 honest reviews for tools you already use. Add one affiliate link per post. Do not chase commission rates; chase trust. Affiliate income compounds when you publish 20-plus evergreen posts.</p>

<h2>Layer 2: Digital products — months 2-3</h2>
<p>Turn your best-performing post into a checklist, template, or mini guide. Sell for $4.99 to $9.99. You already did the research. Packaging is the only extra work.</p>

<h2>Layer 3: Freelance retainers — months 3-5</h2>
<p>Charge $300 to $800/month per client for social media, blog writing, or chatbot setup. One retainer covers your fixed costs and lets the other layers become truly passive.</p>

<h2>Layer 4: Automated funnels — months 6-9</h2>
<p>Set up a simple email sequence around your digital products. 1 welcome email, 3 value emails, 2 pitch emails. Send once, earn on autopilot for months.</p>

<h2>Layer 5: Community or course — month 10+</h2>
<p>Only after you have proof of results. Start with a $27 guide or cohort. Do not build a course before you have case studies.</p>

<h2>The anti-burnout rule</h2>
<ol>
<li>Only focus on one new layer per 30-day period</li>
<li>Automate or template everything you do twice</li>
<li>Stop adding layers once your monthly target is met; optimize instead</li>
</ol>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Remember:</strong> Stacking works only if each layer is repeatable. A one-time $500 gig is not a layer. A $100/month automated asset is.
</div>

